The Coriolis effect is related to Newtonian laws of motion in that it is a consequence of the first law of motion, also known as the law of inertia. When discussing the Coriolis effect, we are referring to the velocity being turned relative to the direction of motion. This happens because rotating objects have an axis of rotation which is always perpendicular to the direction of motion. The Coriolis effect is most often associated with weather.
